image.altText: Cameron Green takes a catch

items.synopsis: Australia's declaration sets India an unlikely 444 runs to win during the fourth day of the World Test Championship final. Follow all the action from The Oval in our live blog.

title.children: Cam Green takes superb, contentious catch to set Australia on its way to victory on day four of WTC final

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The runs required is under 300. Australia is still seven wickets away. Virat Kohli and Ajinkya Rahane played beautifully for that last hour and a bit. It's still a massive longshot, but there will be some belief in the Indian camp tonight. On the whole it's a good day for Australia. They set the massive total and claimed three top order wickets before stumps, but the pace with which India scored and the ease with which this partnership developed is certainly cause for concern. Any complacency will be punished by India at this point. So we're all set up for day five! The World Test Championship final is going the distance, just as we had hoped. Will Australia find those seven wickets and claim the title? Could India hang on for the day, or maybe even chase down this unfathomable total? You'll have to return for tomorrow night's blog to find out. I'll see you then.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: That's stumps! India 3-164 need 280 runs to win

children.content: The runs required is under 300. Australia is still seven wickets away. Virat Kohli and Ajinkya Rahane played beautifully for that last hour and a bit. It's still a massive longshot, but there will be some belief in the Indian camp tonight.

On the whole it's a good day for Australia. They set the massive total and claimed three top order wickets before stumps, but the pace with which India scored and the ease with which this partnership developed is certainly cause for concern. Any complacency will be punished by India at this point.

So we're all set up for day five! The World Test Championship final is going the distance, just as we had hoped. Will Australia find those seven wickets and claim the title? Could India hang on for the day, or maybe even chase down this unfathomable total? You'll have to return for tomorrow night's blog to find out. I'll see you then.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: That's that then. An absolutely enormous, borderline completely impossible target for India to chase and a little over four sessions for Australia to take 10 wickets. First step will be getting through the 40 minutes or so Australia will bowl before tea, before things get trickier yet late in the day. The pitch isn't a minefield, but it's inconsistent, and that will be enough to concern the Indian batters. They'll have to dig in against a rested and fearsome Australian bowling attack, with something special required to avoid defeat.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australia declares at 8-270 - India need 444 runs to win

children.content: That's that then. An absolutely enormous, borderline completely impossible target for India to chase and a little over four sessions for Australia to take 10 wickets. First step will be getting through the 40 minutes or so Australia will bowl before tea, before things get trickier yet late in the day.

The pitch isn't a minefield, but it's inconsistent, and that will be enough to concern the Indian batters. They'll have to dig in against a rested and fearsome Australian bowling attack, with something special required to avoid defeat.
